{"parse":{"title":"Qirad","pageid":9905022,"revid":801506745,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>qirad</b> was one of the basic financial instruments of the <a href=\"/wiki/Islamic_Golden_Age\" title=\"Islamic Golden Age\">medieval Islamic world</a>.  It was an arrangement between one or more investors and an agent where the investors entrusted capital to an agent who then traded with it in hopes of making profit.  Both parties then received a previously settled portion of the profit, though the agent was not liable for any losses.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origins_and_history\">Origins and history</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Qirad&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origins and history\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Although the qirad is never mentioned in the <a href=\"/wiki/Qur%27an\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Qur&#39;an\">Qur'an</a>, many Islamic traditions attribute its origin to the Prophet <a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad\" title=\"Muhammad\">Muhammad</a> and his companions.  These traditions describe <a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad\" title=\"Muhammad\">Muhammad</a> and his companions either using the qirad or endorsing the institution <sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Many will notice that the qirad is almost identical to the institution of the <a href=\"/wiki/Limited_partnership\" title=\"Limited partnership\">commenda</a> later used in western Europe, though whether the qirad transformed into the commenda, or the two institutions evolved independently cannot be stated with certainty.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Legal_technicalities\">Legal technicalities</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Qirad&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Legal technicalities\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Though there existed several different major schools of Islamic law, the basic legalities of the qirad were rather uniform throughout the schools.\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Dinars\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Dinars\">Dinars</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Dirhams\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Dirhams\">dirhams</a>, as well as gold, silver, and copper coins in circulation were allowed to be invested.  However, goods such as barley were restricted from the qirad because the possible fluctuations in their value in the free market.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The agent was allowed to take the investment and split up his investments in any way, as well as invest in anything he wanted,<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> except in cases where stocks are plentiful and not seasonally bound.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MM3235_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MM3235-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> It was also permissible for an investor to forbid the agent from buying certain kinds of goods.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MM3235_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MM3235-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Many of the third parties involved in the qirad were actually unaware of their involvement which allowed the agent to trade freely and without liability.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Although the fractional split in profit was agreed on beforehand, the investor could not stipulate a specific sum of the money from the profit, or that a certain profit be made.  In this way, the qirad remained a complete risk on the investor and did not infringe on the free market economy.,<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> It was however possible to make a deal on the split of the profit beforehand by stipulating a specific percentage. This could be either a low or a high percentage.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MM3235_5-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MM3235-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The principal investment can not be paid back, either by the investor ending the agreement, or the agent ending the agreement, if the principal is still invested in goods. The goods must be sold before the principal can be handed back, and the profits split.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> On the other hand, the investor is allowed to buy goods from the agent if he does not connect any conditions to this transaction.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MM3223_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MM3223-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The agent can also ask the help of a servant of the investor, but this servant also has to share in the profit and can not be asked to do any other work than work connected to the investment.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MM3235_5-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MM3235-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> A servant can also invest in the same investment as his master and also shares in the profit.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MM3223_10-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MM3223-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>If the agent has to hire help for a job, the wage for this person can be paid from the principal, except if the wage should result in loss for the investor, the agent himself is responsible for whatever is not covered by the principal.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The agent can use the principal for food and clothes if he should travel for his business, and the principal is large enough to allow it. If he stays at home this is not allowed.<sup id=\"cite_ref-MM3223_10-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MM3223-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>An agent can invest the money of an investor, the agent then becomes an investor himself, but he is then liable for the losses of the second agent. If the principal decreases, the original investor is allowed to ask the original agent to cover the loss.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Qirad&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Avram Udovitch, \"Partnership and Profit in Medieval Islam\", (Princeton University Press, 1970) p. 170</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Robert H. Hillman, \"Limited Liability in Historical Perspective\", (Washington and Lee Law Review, Spring 1997), Benedikt Koehler, \"Islamic Finance as a Progenitor of Venture Capital\", (Economic Affairs, December 2009)</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Udovitch op cit pp. 177-181</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Malik ibn Anas, al-Muwatta', 280-282 (Kegan Paul International, 1989)</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-MM3235-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-MM3235_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-MM3235_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-MM3235_5-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-MM3235_5-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.iium.edu.my/deed/hadith/malik/032_mmt.html#032.32.3.5\">Malik's Muwatta 32.3.5</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Hillman op cit</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Udovitch op cit, pp. 190-193</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Malik op cit</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.iium.edu.my/deed/hadith/malik/032_mmt.html#032.32.4.6\">Malik's Muwatta 32.4.6</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-MM3223-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-MM3223_10-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-MM3223_10-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-MM3223_10-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.iium.edu.my/deed/hadith/malik/032_mmt.html#032.32.2.3\">Malik's Muwatta 32.2.3</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-11\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-11\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.iium.edu.my/deed/hadith/malik/032_mmt.html#032.32.6.8\">Malik's Muwatta 32.6.8</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-12\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-12\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.iium.edu.my/deed/hadith/malik/032_mmt.html#032.32.8.10\">Malik's Muwatta 32.8.10</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-13\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-13\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.iium.edu.my/deed/hadith/malik/032_mmt.html#032.32.7.9\">Malik's Muwatta 32.7.9</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<div role=\"navigation\" class=\"navbox\" aria-labelledby=\"Islamic_banking_and_finance\" style=\"padding:3px\"><table class=\"nowraplinks collapsible autocollapse navbox-inner\" style=\"border-spacing:0;background:transparent;color:inherit\"><tbody><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"navbox-title\" colspan=\"2\"><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Islamic_banking_and_finance\" title=\"Template:Islamic banking and finance\"><abbr title=\"View this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Islamic_banking_and_finance\" title=\"Template talk:Islamic banking and finance\"><abbr title=\"Discuss this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">t</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-edit\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Islamic_banking_and_finance&amp;action=edit\"><abbr title=\"Edit this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">e</abbr></a></li>